<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="636" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[111,648,1308,1570]" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">
DIAGNOSIS. — Scorpion of small size with a total length of 
<quantity box="[135,259,1334,1358]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" unit="mm" value="40.0" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="35.0">35 to 45 mm</quantity>
. General coloration yellowish; metasomal segments IV and V almost blackish. Carapace and tergites weakly granular. Pectines: pectinal teeth count in average 
<quantity box="[112,191,1414,1438]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.382" metricValueMax="8.636" metricValueMin="8.128" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" unit="in" value="33.0" valueMax="34.0" valueMin="32.0">32-34 in</quantity>
males and 
<quantity box="[290,369,1414,1438]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.731" metricValueMax="7.366" metricValueMin="6.096" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" unit="in" value="26.5" valueMax="29.0" valueMin="24.0">24-29 in</quantity>
females; basal middle lamellae of each pecten not dilated in males; dilated and elongated in females; just after the base, to the apex, covering 4 to 5 most proximal teeth. Dorsal carinae on segments II to IV without any posterior spinoid granule. Fixed and movable fingers with 11-11 oblique rows of granules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="636" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[112,648,1596,1700]" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">
DISTRIBUTION AND ECOLOGY. — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fage" authorityYear="1929" box="[456,646,1596,1620]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulatus">
<emphasis box="[456,646,1596,1620]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">Grosphus annulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="FAGE L." box="[373,488,1622,1647]" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" pagination="637 - 694" refId="ref7504" refString="FAGE L. 1929. - Les Scorpions de Madagascar. Faune des Colonies francaises 3. Societe d'Editions Geographiques Maritimes Coloniales, Paris: 637 - 694." type="book chapter" year="1929">Fage (1929)</bibRefCitation>
only as a variety, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fage, 1929" authorityName="Fage" authorityYear="1929" box="[112,493,1649,1673]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="limbatus" variety="annulata">
<emphasis box="[112,370,1649,1673]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">G. limbatus var. annulata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="FAGE L." box="[378,493,1649,1673]" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" pagination="637 - 694" refId="ref7504" refString="FAGE L. 1929. - Les Scorpions de Madagascar. Faune des Colonies francaises 3. Societe d'Editions Geographiques Maritimes Coloniales, Paris: 637 - 694." type="book chapter" year="1929">Fage, 1929</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. More detailed studies indicated that it was necessary to elevate this
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[675,1212,215,847]" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">
form to the rank of species (
<bibRefCitation author="LOURENCO W. R." box="[950,1108,215,239]" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" refId="ref7808" refString="LOURENCO W. R. 1996. - Scorpions (Chelicerata, Scorpiones). Coll. Faune de Madagascar, Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, 87, 102 p." type="book" year="1996">Lourenço 1996</bibRefCitation>
). It can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Pocock, 1889)" baseAuthorityName="Pocock" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[934,1209,241,265]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbatus">
<emphasis box="[934,1049,241,265]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">G. limbatus</emphasis>
(Pocock, 1889)
</taxonomicName>
by a characteristic pigmentation pattern – the carapace and tergites are extensively yellowish, but the metasomal segments IV and V are markedly blackish. Based on pigmentation patterns, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fage" authorityYear="1929" box="[907,1030,347,371]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulatus">
<emphasis box="[907,1030,347,371]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">G. annulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenco, 2004" authorityName="Lourenco" authorityYear="2004" box="[783,1043,374,398]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis box="[783,866,374,398]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">G. olgae</emphasis>
Lourenço, 2004
</taxonomicName>
described from South-Western 
<collectingCountry box="[833,950,400,424]" name="Madagascar" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
(see below). These species can, however, be distinguished from one another based on the shape of basal middle lamellae of the female pectines, and distinct shape differences in the telson. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fage" authorityYear="1929" box="[707,838,506,530]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulatus">
<emphasis box="[707,838,506,530]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">G. annulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the vesicle is strongly globular and longer than the aculeus, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lourenco" authorityYear="2004" box="[1002,1079,532,556]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis box="[1002,1079,532,556]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">G. olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the vesicle is weakly globular and shorter than the aculeus (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[113,124,1483,1501]" captionTargetBox="[128,1193,235,1427]" captionTargetId="figure-91@6.[113,1209,215,1453]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 3. Ỏ Grophus ssp., Metasomal segment V and telson,lateral aspect:A, B, Grosphus annulatus Fage,1929:A, male paralectotype; B, female lectotype; C, D, Grosphus intertidalis LourenÁo, 1999, male (C) and female (D); E, F, Grosphus mahafaliensis LourenÁo, Goodman &amp; Ramilijaona, 2004, male (E) and female (F). Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539578/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">Figs 3A, B</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[707,771,585,609]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[113,124,1509,1527]" captionTargetBox="[125,1188,231,1475]" captionTargetId="figure-74@8.[113,1209,215,1484]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 4. Ỏ Grophus ssp., Metasomal segment V and telson, lateral aspect: A, B, Grosphus olgae LourenÁo, 2004, male (A) and female (B) paratypes; C, Grosphus feti LourenÁo, 1996, male holotype; D, Grosphus rossii LourenÁo, 2013, male holotype; E, Grosphus magalieae n. sp., male holotype. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539580" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539580/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">4A, B</figureCitation>
). Given all of the fieldwork conducted in South-Western 
<collectingCountry box="[841,964,612,636]" name="Madagascar" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, it is rather remarkable that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fage" authorityYear="1929" box="[721,846,638,662]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Grosphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="636" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulatus">
<emphasis box="[721,846,638,662]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">G. annulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from the original 
<typeStatus box="[1167,1209,639,663]" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">type</typeStatus>
locality of “Province 
<collectingRegion box="[874,942,665,689]" country="Madagascar" name="Toliara" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">Toliara</collectingRegion>
[
<collectingRegion box="[952,1028,665,689]" country="Madagascar" name="Toliara" pageId="5" pageNumber="636">Toliara</collectingRegion>
], Sarodrano” (
<bibRefCitation author="FAGE L." pageId="5" pageNumber="636" pagination="637 - 694" refId="ref7504" refString="FAGE L. 1929. - Les Scorpions de Madagascar. Faune des Colonies francaises 3. Societe d'Editions Geographiques Maritimes Coloniales, Paris: 637 - 694." type="book chapter" year="1929">Fage 1929</bibRefCitation>
). The coastal sand dune habitat surrounding the Sarodrano area has not been the subject of a recent inventory using pit-fall traps and perhaps this taxon has very specific ecological requirements. Fresh material will be needed for molecular studies to resolve the relationships of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
